ection takes flower remedies and imagines how each plant would deal with the malady it was supposed to correct","byline":"Kate Kellaway","body":"<p>How often is a poetry collection a collection? It is a rare thing for every poem to get on with its neighbours, but one of the pleasures of reading Katharine Towers’s beautiful poems is that they belong together. I kept thinking, as I read, of Shakespeare’s word for herbs and flowers: “simples”. These are simples, remedies for the eye and mind. And yet the opening poem, The Roses, is an unusual mixture of peace and violent emotion. The roses are the medium through which Towers remembers her father and conjures him for an impossible, unpruned moment, back to life. Later in the collection – the two poems placed like symmetrical windows – she imagines her mother alive, only to let her go and, in a sense, become her mother herself – part of what it is to mourn a parent.</p> <p>This is Towers’s second collection (her first was longlisted for the <em>Guardian’s</em> first book award). And there is so much to praise about the writing: clarity, generosity and grace. There are no barriers between poem and reader. Individual verbs give a frisson of pleasure because they are exactly right: frost “enunciates” the day, an enormous cloud “lolled” against a hill, the sea is “rummaging” to find weaknesses in the cliff. She knows less is more. Reading between the lines is our fine task, listening to what is not quite spoken. And as a linguist (there are a couple of splendid poems about translation) she is interested in the limbo between languages, the teasing nature of the apparently inexpressible.</p> <p>She writes with a marvellously gentle wit and a metrical intelligence. I particularly love her poem Chaffinch. The bird emerges as an inferior but admirably persistent artist (one knows the sort of chap she is talking about):</p> <p><em>… and no-one has told him</em><br /><em>he always sounds the same.</em><br /><em>Never bored, he understands</em><br /><em>that moments must be uttered</em><br /><em>and moments do not matter –</em></p> <p>She may be ribbing the bird but also identifies the unfashionable truth about time he embodies. She is alive to the liberties poets take in appropriating nature and seems on the edge of applying a restraining hand to her own pen – fortunately never succeeding in silencing herself. In Murmuration, a wonderful poem about starlings, she reflects as she watches their flight: “none of this is about us”. In Childhood, a breathtaking song of innocence and experience, she interrogates scrutiny: “We should not be looking so hard/at what a tree would rather keep to itself”. And in Bluebells, she reflects on the way that flowers have no choice but to return each year and be blue. Whatever a poet makes of them, they are helplessly themselves.</p> <p>This may explain the book’s provocatively fanciful core in which she takes <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2001/sep/01/shopping\" title=\"\">Dr Bach’s 1930s flower remedies</a> and imagines how it would be were each flower or plant afflicted with the malaise it was intended to cure. It is another way of defying what human beings have imposed and, in less skilful hands, might have been a whimsical disaster. But these poems, each written in the first person – Agrimony, Aspen, Water Violet, Early Gentian and many more – are a joy. I particularly love Willow, said to be a “remedy for self-pity”. For the willow: “water is always upon me/like a bad thought./For all the good I have not done… Forgive me, forgive me.” Quite how she manages the balancing act between entertainment and something that comes close to a prayer, that catches at your throat, is beyond me.</p> <h2>Childhood by Katharine Towers<br /></h2> <p>These criss-cross lines printed on the snow<br />are bones of trees laid bare by the moon.<br />We should not be looking so hard</p> <p>at what a tree would rather keep to itself.<br />Would we not fear to be shown<br />how like replicas we are, and how mechanical?</p> <p>Let’s play that game again, stepping out<br />along the branches – pretending to tip –<br />as if we still believed we couldn’t fall.</p> <p><em>The Remedies by Katharine Towers is published by Picador (£9.99). </em><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/remedies-423087.html?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\" title=\"\"><em>Click here to order a copy for £8.19 </em></a></p>","wordcount":"679","commentCloseDate":"2016-09-05T09:45:00Z","commentable":"true","productionOffice":"UK","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/4ptth","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/e68c165fae2f736912663766bf2221aab5817628/0_222_3354_2012/500.jpg"},"tags":[{"id":"books/poetry","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Poetry","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/poetry","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/poetry","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","type":"keyword","sectionId":"culture","sectionName":"Culture","webTitle":"Culture","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","references":[]},{"id":"tone/reviews","type":"tone","webTitle":"Reviews","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/tone/reviews","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/tone/reviews","references":[]},{"id":"tracking/commissioningdesk/observer-new-review","type":"tracking","webTitle":"Observer New Review","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/tracking/commissioningdesk/observer-new-review","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/tracking/commissioningdesk/observer-new-review","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","type":"type","webTitle":"Article","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.c