","webPublicationDate":"2016-08-14T09:00:31Z","webTitle":"The Heart Goes Last by Margaret Atwood review – visceral study of desperation","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/aug/14/the-heart-goes-last-margaret-atwood-review","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/aug/14/the-heart-goes-last-margaret-atwood-review","fields":{"headline":"The Heart Goes Last by Margaret Atwood review – visceral study of desperation","standfirst":"Margaret Atwood’s latest dystopian vision is full of acute intellectual and emotional insight","trailText":"Margaret Atwood’s latest dystopian vision is full of acute intellectual and emotional insight","byline":"Anita Sethi","body":"<p>The pounding of the heart echoes throughout Margaret Atwood’s engrossing 56th book, beating in fear that it will soon beat no more. Charmaine and her husband, Stan, live in their cramped car, having lost their home and jobs in a financial collapse that has turned the north-east of the US into “a festering scrapheap”.</p> <p>Survival is all for our protagonists. People have been reduced to selling their bodies, souls, even their blood. Dystopias have been brilliantly evoked by Atwood, from <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/jan/20/handmaids-tale-margaret-atwood\"><em>The Handmaid’s Tale</em></a> to the MaddAddam trilogy, and her latest pulses with profound questions: what lengths would you go to survive? What compromises would you make? What would make someone kill the thing they most love?</p> <p>One day, Charmaine sees an advert for the Positron Project, promising she “can be the person she’s always wanted to be”. Having barely read the terms and conditions, the couple sign the binding “commitment papers” and relocate to the town of Consilience, “because Charmaine has her heart set on it”. Here is a story showing what desperation does to the human heart.</p> <p>Prohibitions abound here. Everyone must live two lives: one month they have a home and job but the next they must live in a prison, swapping with their “Alternates”. Although there is a “strict Consilience taboo against contact with Alternates”, Charmaine and Stan cannot help imagining alternative lives with alternative partners and are so tantalised by the possibilities that they pursue them to devastating effect.</p> <p>In the tightly controlled environment (where “they censor anything too arousing or disruptive”, including rock music and hip-hop), characters nevertheless lose control, governed by their “tormented desires”.</p> <p>The increasingly bizarre plot takes in subterfuge, sex slaves, human organ trafficking and identity erasure. But it is the details that are most emotionally engaging, as characters cling on to their last vestiges of humanity: the moment, on realising the truth, when “Charmaine’s heart sinks”; the moment her husband’s “heart beats like percussion under her fingertips”; the moment a serial adulterer assures his wife “he’s loyal to her in his heart”.</p> <p>This visceral study of desperation and desire journeys into the dark heart of greed, exploitation and brutality, as it portrays a project that is “an infringement of individual liberties, an attempt at total social control, an insult to the human spirit”. It is filled with passages of great intellectual and emotional acuity, appealing both to the head and to the heart.</p> <p><em> The Heart Goes Last is published by Virago (£8.99). </em><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/heart-goes-last.html?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\"><em>Click here to a copy for £7.37 </em></a></p>","wordcount":"428","commentCloseDate":"2016-09-04T09:45:00Z","commentable":"true","productionOffice":"UK","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/4ptgx","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/09a86944c146b23f09b10b4fdc98dabf0cae0cc9/0_192_5760_3456/500.jpg"},"tags":[{"id":"books/margaretatwood","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Margaret Atwood","webUrl":"ht