e":"https://media.guim.co.uk/09a86944c146b23f09b10b4fdc98dabf0cae0cc9/0_192_5760_3456/500.jpg","displayCredit":"true","mediaId":"09a86944c146b23f09b10b4fdc98dabf0cae0cc9","imageType":"Photograph","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/09a86944c146b23f09b10b4fdc98dabf0cae0cc9"}}]}],"references":[],"rights":{"syndicatable":"true","subscriptionDatabases":"false","developerCommunity":"false"},"section":{"id":"books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books","editions":[{"id":"books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books","code":"default"}]},"isHosted":false},{"id":"books/2016/aug/14/lionel-shriver-a-lunch-invitation-is-a-catastrophe-night-own-interview-mandibles","type":"article","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webPublicationDate":"2016-08-14T08:00:30Z","webTitle":"Lionel Shriver: ‘A lunch invitation is a catastrophe’","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/aug/14/lionel-shriver-a-lunch-invitation-is-a-catastrophe-night-own-interview-mandibles","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/aug/14/lionel-shriver-a-lunch-invitation-is-a-catastrophe-night-own-interview-mandibles","fields":{"headline":"Lionel Shriver: ‘A lunch invitation is a catastrophe’","standfirst":"The novelist, writer and night owl on the pros and cons of keeping odd hours","trailText":"The novelist, writer and night owl on the pros and cons of keeping odd hours","byline":"Alex Clark","body":"<p>Lionel Shriver is the author of 13 novels, including the Orange prize-winning <em>We Need to Talk About Kevin</em>, <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/may/11/big-brother-lionel-shriver-review\"><em>Big Brother</em></a><em> </em>and her most recent, <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/may/18/the-mandibles-a-family-2029-2047-by-lionel-shriver\"><em>The Mandibles</em></a>. She grew up in North Carolina, and now lives in London, with forays to the US, where she was when the <em>Observer </em>spoke to her.</p> <p><strong>You are a seasoned night owl. What’s the story?</strong><br />I gravitate to a schedule whereby I end up going to sleep at about 4am, and I don’t know why exactly. I used to identify <em>Newsnight </em>being broadcast at 10.30pm as the source of all my ills, but even when I’m away from <em>Newsnight</em> in the United States I end up keeping to the same schedule. I don’t think it’s exotic. It’s the same thing that everybody does: I get tired and go to sleep and get up, just later in the day.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>You do not say: 'I’m sorry. I cannot do this interview at 10.30am. I will be asleep.' Nobody takes that as an excuse</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p><strong>Is there something about the solitude and quiet that fits with writing?</strong><br />Yes. When I’ve got a book on the boil, and especially when my husband’s out of the country, which he often is, and in the winter when the sun goes down at three o’clock, I have a segment of time until 10pm when I can get work done. There is something about the lighting, with the desk lamp on, and it’s dark outside; it creates a little cocoon that’s very warm and protective and quiet and focused. And I do like that.</p> <p><strong>And what about after your writing stint?</strong><br />After I’m finished working, I always do my exercise, and then I’ll eat something, usually after midnight. The main problem with that routine is all these people who want to do things in the morning.</p> <p><strong>How do you deal with them?</strong><br />I try to fend them off to the best of my ability. But I can’t always. UK tradesmen in particular have a thing about showing up at 8am; they like to get their work done super-early and knock off at two in the afternoon. So we’re on completely different schedules. When there’s something that needs repairing, which is all the time, I get no sleep, fundamentally. I don’t find it possible to say oh, today I’m going to go to sleep at 9pm. It’s a real downside. I’m not recommending people adopt this schedule.</p> <p><strong>Do you ever just not answer the door, say to the postman?</strong><br />Well, the worst of both worlds is that I scramble into my robe, and hustle downstairs in what is to me the middle of the night, and I still miss the delivery. That’s standard. The rest of the temporally normal world don’t understand when you keep trying to schedule things in the afternoon. And I don’t want to get into it with them, so I sometimes I pretend that I have appointments in the morning. You do not say: “I’m sorry. I cannot do this interview at 10.30 in the morning. I will be asleep.” Nobody takes that as an excuse.</p> <p><strong>There is a kind of morality attached to being the early bird, isn’t there?</strong><br />The disapproval is unbelievable. And I get that even from delivery people. If I do hustle downstairs at 10.30 – and they probably got up at 5 – the contempt drips off them. I have to actually stop myself from saying: you don’t understand, I’m not some layabout. I actually have a job. I just keep different hours.</p> <p><strong>Your husband is a musician; does that make life easier?</strong><br />Yes. Jazz musicians work at night, they also stay up very late. He doesn’t make a habit of it, but it’s not extraordinary for my husband to get back at five, even six in the morning. At which point, he will find me in bed.</p> <p><strong>Being nocturnal does help when dramatic events unfold in the small hours, like Brexit, for example…</strong><br />I have to admit, I missed Brexit, and I rue that. I was so sure that Remain was going to win that I wasn’t filled with a sense of suspense, and I didn’t go out of my way to make sure I stayed in the UK to experience it. If I had known what I know now, I would have stuck around an extra week before coming to the US. As it happened, I did stay up here, until the result was in, and I was absolutely floored. We stayed up until Cameron’s resignation speech – it’s a little easier to stay up here because we’re five hours behind. Even so, I don’t think that night we got to sleep until 5am.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"c66288125e54df7bcc26fc32ed5582438b6aab80\"> <img src=\"https://media.guim.co.uk/c66288125e54df7bcc26fc32ed5582438b6aab80/6_152_2470_1642/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Lionel Shriver runs past Battle of Britain memorial in London\" width=\"1000\" height=\"665\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Lionel Shriver, who prefers to exercise at night, runs past the Battle of Britain memorial in London.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Henry Browne</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p><strong>You’re in the US at the moment – how’s that working with the current news cycle?</strong><br />The problem is that watching these conventions is unendurable. I hate political cant. It doesn’t even matter whether they’re good or bad performances. Bullshit is bullshit, right?</p> <p><strong>Are you in a novel-writing phase at the minute?</strong><br />Not right now. I’m working on a short story, but my productivity always goes down during the summer. I play a lot of tennis. And it’s hot.</p> <p><strong>You usually run at night, don’t you?</strong><br />Yes, although not in New York. And I play tennis during the day. One of the nice things, though, on the days that I’m not playing tennis, is exercising at night – nine, 10 o’clock. It’s much more bearable.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>Soon more people will be able to function with the schedule that suits them and I will become less weird</p> </blockquote> </aside>  <p><strong>What happens if someone asks you to lunch?</strong><br />Well, that’s a catastrophe. I have a rule against lunch, and I break that rule maybe once or twice a year, only for professional emergencies. Basically that’s a breakfast meeting. In fact, I had somebody propose a real breakfast meeting recently, and I was warned that it would be early. Obviously it would be like, 7am. I would have to stay up! I’d show up for the breakfast meeting expecting to have a cognac. It would do my reputation a world of good.</p> <p><strong>When we met at an event recently, you had just interviewed Damian Lewis, who was opening the Stock Exchange at 8am. Not the easiest commission for your body clock to handle…?</strong><br />Oh yes, I remember that. I was in training for days for that interview. But I was still way underslept for meeting someone who is not only famous, but also, it turns out, quite articulate and smart. I ended up being fortunate that he’s not only articulate and smart but rather garrulous, and I didn’t have to say very much.</p> <p><strong>Your latest novel, <em>The Mandibles</em>, is concerned with the future of economics, social structures and work patterns. Do you have a concept of what a 24-hour society might look like?</strong><br />I think we are certainly drifting towards many more people being self-employed, and who therefore make their own hours. And even people who are not self-employed are now being released to work at home at least a proportion of their week, and therefore have themselves to report to. There are whole corporations that have stopped making people clock in and don’t care any more how many hours you put in; all they care about is whether you get your work done. Which I think is great – it’s definitely a more intelligent organising principle. It means that people who naturally drift in the direction I do are going to be able to function with the schedule that suits them. So what we’re talking about will become more and more prevalent, and I will become less weird.</p> <p><strong>Would you actually like that, or is it more fun swimming against the tide?</strong><br />Right now I don’t care, but if the many other trends are anything to go by, whereby things that I’ve always done that were a little odd end up being adopted by the rest of the world, I’ll probably feel a bit resentful. Like, who are all these people? Go away. I’m supposed to be the only one who’s awake here.</p> <p><em>The Mandibles: A Family 2029-2047 is published by Borough Press, £16.99. </em><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/the-mandibles-a-family-2029-2047.html\"><em>Click here to buy it for £12.99</em></a></p>","wordcount":"1382","commentCloseDate":"2016-08-30T18:24:00Z","commentable":"true","productionOffice":"UK","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/4q7ag","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/3da03de6cfd1d946db76de1447cd49d799517fc5/157_873_3751_2251/500.jpg"},"tags":[{"id":"books/lionel-shriver","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Lionel Shriver","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/lionel-shriver","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/lionel-shriver","references":[]},{"id":"theobserver/series/night-time-uncovered","type":"series","sectionId":"theobserver","sectionName":"From the Observer","webTitle":"Night-time uncovered","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/series/night-time-uncovered","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/series/night-time-uncovered","references":[],"description":"<p>An Observer special, ahead of London's 24-hour tube</p>"},{"id":"books/books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","references":[]},{"id":"theobserver/series/the-new-review-q-and-a","type":"series","sectionId":"theobserver","sectionName":"From the Observer","webTitle":"The New Review Q&A","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/series/the-new-review-q-and-a","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/theobserver/series/the-new-review-q-and-a","references":[]