s.com/books","code":"default"}]},"isHosted":false},{"id":"books/2016/aug/14/the-empathy-problem-gavin-extence-review","type":"article","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webPublicationDate":"2016-08-14T08:00:30Z","webTitle":"The Empathy Problem by Gavin Extence review","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/aug/14/the-empathy-problem-gavin-extence-review","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/aug/14/the-empathy-problem-gavin-extence-review","fields":{"headline":"The Empathy Problem by Gavin Extence – review","standfirst":"A dying hedge fund manager’s redemption is a promising idea, but the tale rings hollow","trailText":"A dying hedge fund manager’s redemption is a promising idea, but the tale rings hollow","byline":"Hannah Beckerman","body":"<p>When novelists decide to write a book about contemporary political or social events, they always engage in a narrative gamble: will the episodes they’re choosing to chronicle still feel timely and relevant come publication?</p> <p>Short of being in possession of a crystal ball, there was no way Gavin Extence could have known, as he sat down to write his third novel, <em>The Empathy Problem</em>, a story about a London hedge fund manager set against the backdrop of the <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/occupy\">2011/2012 Occupy movement,</a> that by the time the novel was published, the Occupy camp outside St Paul’s would feel historical rather than contemporary. There was no way he could have predicted that the banking crisis would have long since been replaced in the headlines by the Syrian refugee crisis, the EU referendum, Islamic State and almost weekly terror attacks across Europe. As such, the backdrop for a story Extence no doubt conceived of as a state-of-the-nation tale instead feels curiously anachronistic.</p> <p>Political backdrop aside, the idea for <em>The Empathy Problem</em> holds much promise. A 32-year-old hedge fund manager, Gabriel Vaughn, discovers he has a brain tumour and only six months to live. The diagnosis – or perhaps the tumour itself – begins to alter Gabriel’s behaviour profoundly , transforming him from a selfish, self-absorbed and self-aggrandising sociopath into someone who experiences – for the first time – feelings of empathy, love and slivers of social conscience.</p> <p>This is an enticing premise, with its elements of redemption. And much like Extence’s bestselling debut novel in 2013 – <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/feb/17/universe-alex-woods-extence-review\"><em>The Universe Versus Alex Woods</em></a>, which won the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waterstones_11\">Waterstones 11</a> prize – it is the kind of plot that makes you want to enjoy the book before reading has begun.</p> <p>Unfortunately, <em>The Empathy Problem</em> never quite delivers on its emotional potential and the redemptive course of action Gabriel embarks upon feels underwhelming and hollow. Rather than, for instance, using the last six months of his life, and his extreme wealth, to some greater social good, Extence’s protagonist chooses to wreak financial revenge on his employers and colleagues, which even he admits at the end of the book won’t effect any lasting change: “They’ve taken a small hit to their personal fortunes, but they’re still multimillionaires. They get to walk away from this relatively unscathed. In that sense, I’m not sure anything I did made a huge difference.”</p> <p>He sells his flat to an oligarch, despite his suspicions that the purchase is purely for money-laundering purposes, and is unable to part company with his beloved yellow Ferrari. None of this creates the emotionally edifying story the book could have been. Gabriel does help the 11 secretaries at his firm escape their menial and unfulfilling jobs, but this feels like a small victory in a novel that had the potential to be a genuinely life-affirming narrative.</p> <p>The Occupy backdrop is also underutilised. It serves as a physical manifestation of Gabriel’s conscience – his office window overlooks the camp and the sight of it increasingly unsettles him – and it is the place where he meets the novel’s love interest, Caitlin. There is a scene in which Gabriel meets a number of protesters, leading to some rather heavy-handed political discussions and pointed character self-justifications, but beyond this, the two story strands never really coalesce.</p> <p>Although the central relationship in <em>The Empathy Problem</em> is between Gabriel and Caitlin, whose romantic trajectory follows a conventional path of love, loss and reconciliation, it is the encounters between Gabriel and his father that provide the most touching moments. Emotionally estranged since the death of Gabriel’s mother, there is a quiet tragedy to their inability to communicate.</p> <p>This is a novel that never quite gets under the skin of its story or its characters. Unlike the financial gambles that have made Gabriel a millionaire, Extence’s creative gamble never quite reaps the potential rewards.</p> <p><em> The Empathy Problem is published by Hodder &amp; Stoughton (£16.99). </em><a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/empathy-problem.html?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\"><em>Click here to order it for £13.93 </em></a></p>","wordcount":"665","commentCloseDate":"2016-09-04T08:45:00Z","commentable":"true","productionOffice":"UK","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/4ptbf","thumbnail":"https://media.guim.co.uk/2fde4202bae9e2ff1ab68fca0bb39c955c589095/0_59_5616_3370/500.jpg"},"tags":[{"id":"books/fiction","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Fiction","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/fiction","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/books/fiction","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","sectionName":"Books","webTitle":"Books","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"https://content.guar